<seg id=1> Guangxi Uses US$150 Million in Foreign Capital to Build Basic Transportation and Water Transport Facilities </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua New Agency, Nanning, March 14, Telegram (Reporter Lu Hankui):  According to information released by the Transportation Department of the Guangxi Zhuangzu Autonomous Region, as of today, Guangxi has borrowed US$150 million from the World Bank, Asia Bank, Holland, South Korea, and other countries to build basic transportation and water transport facilities. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> In the past few years, construction in the greater Southwest region of China has been accelerated by the Guangxi thoroughfare to the sea. </seg>
<seg id=4> To solve the problem of inadequate capital and to further open up to the outside, Guangxi has expended great effort in attracting foreign investment. </seg>
<seg id=5> In the West River Shipping Hub Phase Two Project involving a total investment of more than 2 billion Renminbi, US$80 million were borrowed from the World Bank.  At present, excavation on the main project is already 80 percent complete and the poured concrete construction is already 50 percent complete. </seg>
<seg id=6> In the Fangchenggang City Phase Two Project (including the highway from Qinzhou City to Fangchenggang City), a loan of US$52 million from the Asian Development Bank has been employed and it is expected that the highway will be completed and opened for use in the latter half of this year. </seg>
<seg id=7> A loan of US$10 million from the South Korean government has been employed for the Beihai Harbor conveyance facility construction project. </seg>
<seg id=8> A loan of US$13 million from the Dutch government has been employed for the Qinzhou Harbor conveyance facility construction project. </seg>
<seg id=9> All of these engineering projects are progressing smoothly. </seg>
</p>
